                        <additions>
                            <p>
                                <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/>
                                <note>Top left corner in pencil by a modern hand: <quote>97 <unclear quantity="8" unit="chars" reason="illegible"/> S. Brigittae <unclear quantity="4" unit="chars" reason="illegible"/>
                                    </quote>; centre page: the medieval book plate of <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102585">Hilprand Brandenburg</persName>; below, in pencil by a modern hand: <quote>Ex libr<supplied reason="omitted">is</supplied> Hildebrani fl<supplied reason="omitted">oruit</supplied> 1500 - F<unclear quantity="4" unit="chars" reason="illegible"/>
                                    </quote>; below: modern stamp of National Library; bottom left corner: National Library book label with the current signum; bottom right corner in pencil: <quote>H 2</quote>; below, in blue ink: the year of accession and accession number, <quote>1944/14</quote>.</note>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                <locus from="RCI" to="RCI" scheme="other"/>
                                <note>Top left corner: a glued-on paper label, torn, but with the number <quote>3</quote> legible.</note>
                            </p>
                        </additions>
                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding contemporary="true">
                                <p>Medieval binding. Grayish white leather over bevelled wooden boards. 3 double raised bands and endbands. 1 hooked clasp. <locus from="Spine" to="Spine" scheme="other"/>: in brown ink on a paper label <quote>Regula S. Salvatoris Offic. et Legenda S. Brigitte Vidue</quote>; below, stamped in gold: <quote>A 75a</quote>; below: the remains of another paper label; <locus from="LCO" to="LCO" scheme="other"/>, top: traces of writing in brown ink, barely legible [Regula Sancti Salvatoris?]; <locus from="LCO" to="LCO" scheme="other"/>, bottom, in pencil: <quote>378[3?]</quote>.</p>
                                <p>
                                    <dimensions type="binding">
                                        <height quantity="175" unit="mm"/>
                                        <width quantity="120" unit="mm"/>
                                        <depth quantity="35" unit="mm"/>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </p>
                                <decoNote type="tooling">
                                    <p>
                                        <locus from="LCO" to="LCO" scheme="other"/> and <locus from="RCO" to="RCO" scheme="other"/>, blind tooled triple-line borders, inside of which a blind tooled pattern of lozenges; at each intersection of the diagonal lines, a blind stamped flower; at the centre of each lozenge (or triangle), a blind stamped fleur-de-lis in a double-line lozenge-shaped frame, or a blind stamped acorn.</p>
                                </decoNote>
                                <condition>Leather somewhat worn; in a few places, wormholes which have penetrated the wooden boards. Clasp and strap missing.</condition>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                    </physDesc>
                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <p>
                                <origPlace>
                                    <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100104">Germany</placeName>
                                    <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100252">Maihingen</placeName>
                                </origPlace>, <origDate notAfter="1500" notBefore="1476">15th century, last quarter</origDate>; see colophon on <locus from="78v" to="78v" scheme="folios"/>.</p>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>Once owned by the Carthusian monks at <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100251">Buxheim</placeName> (<locus from="1r" to="1r" scheme="folios"/>). <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/> carries the bookplate of <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102585">Hilprand Brandenburg</persName>, a donate of the community at Buxheim, who bequeathed ca 450 books to the monks there before his death in <date when="1514"/>. Collijn, however, questions that this manuscript formed part of Hilprand's donation; he suggests that the bookplate may instead have been inserted by an antiquarian later in its history (<bibl>
                                    <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107275">Collijn (1945)</title>
                                    <citedRange from="9" to="9" unit="page"/>
                                </bibl>).</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>Purchased by <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100004">the National Library</orgName> from the baroness <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102598">Elise Åkerhielm</persName> of Anneberg, <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100258">Gustavsberg</placeName>, <date when="1944-09-22"/>.</p>
                        </acquisition>
                    </history>
